description:
Applicants for an ACT public vehicle driver licence must meet eligibility requirements as set out in the Road Transport (Driver Licensing) Regulation 2000.

Access Canberra must confirm your identity prior to completing driver licence transactions. If you do not hold, or cannot produce, your ACT Driver Licence, you may be required to provide full proof of identity and/or residency. Further information about identity requirements can be found on the proof of identity and residency page.

Public vehicle driver licence conditions are:

T - Taxi;
O - Public bus;
H - Hire car;
M - Hire car motorcycle;
W - Restricted hire car; and,
D - Rideshare.
Eligibility requirements for all public vehicle driver licence applications include you:

are a permanent Australian resident or have a visa that allows you to work in Australia;
hold a full Australian driver licence; and,
read and comply with all the requirements on this page.
Additional eligibility requirements for specific public vehicle driver licence conditions include:

Application for an 'O' condition - you hold a full Australian C or higher class licence and have done for at least 1 year (or for periods totalling 1 year) in the last 3 years.

Application for an 'M' condition – you hold a full Australian motorcycle licence.

Please see the Rideshare accreditation and licensing in the ACT page.

a T (taxi) condition
You must provide a language skills assessment certificate if you are not a citizen or passport holder from one of the following countries:

Australia;
Canada;
New Zealand;
Republic of Ireland;
United Kingdom; or
USA.
an O (public bus) condition
an M (hire car motorcycle) condition
D (Rideshare) condition
Applicants may not be issued with a public vehicle driver licence where the applicant has within the last 5 years:

been convicted of a disqualifying offence;
been disqualified from holding or obtaining an Australian driver licence under the law of any jurisdiction; or,
had their driver licence suspended under the law of any jurisdiction other than for the non-payment of an infringement notice penalty.
While operating a public vehicle, you must have a blood alcohol content (BAC) of 0.

